@flyingsnake3737 There was always going to be an extremist regime in Germany because of the stipulations of the Versailles treaty. The SA outnumbered the Reichswehr (limited to 100,000 personnel by the aforementioned treaty) 40 to 1 and most would've had no qualms destroying German state institutions such as the armed forces since they were explicitly loyal to the NSDAP and not Germany. If the Reichswehr took up arms against the NSDAP, it would've been obliterated in very short order and replaced with the Wehrmacht soon after. The Reichswehr did actually try to kind of sort of curb the NSDAP by playing a major role in pushing for the Night of the Long Knives, but that was of course for matters of self-preservation and not for helping Germany to get free of the NSDAP.

Anyway, what I'm saying is that the Treaty of Versailles and the climate of early 20th-century Europe combined to pretty much guarantee that the Weimar Republic would fall to extremism sooner or later, and Germany would've been almost certainly steered in the direction of crimes against peace once again by whoever came to power. There's nothing that any one neutral institution could've really done to upend Hitler and the party, even (or maybe especially) early on. In the years between 1934 and 1939, the Wehrmacht was established and grew rapidly and could've maybe done something about Hitler if it had the will, but I'm still skeptical because of the relatively high popularity of the NSDAP among the German people and the thorough Nazification of most state institutions, like the police, as well as the growing influence and power of the SS (even before the war started and the SS ballooned the way it did.)

The Wehrmacht still should've at least *tried* to remove the NSDAP, undo the Enabling Act, etc. in 1938 or 39, before the war started, that much I can say and I think you'd agree.

